: Since the earlier posting, we've heard elsewhere that Phil Zimmerman has 
: also received a subpoena.  I believe that *his* goal which was to spread 
: the use of strong crypto was certainly achieved.  Debate on this topic is 
: also more vigorous than it was before PGP (which was another goal).

: S >If the second subpoena mentioned by Grady is indeed as represented, 
: S >this is VERY serious business, because his associates are asked to
: S >appear in front of a Grand Jury. This is not a simple inquiry, but the 
: S >first step in a prosecution. If the Grand Jury indicts, the matter can
: S >be extremely costly and painful, 

: Unless those being prosecuted are judgment proof.   I would urge all those 
: undertaking such hazardous activities to make themselves judgment proof in 
: advance.  It makes things much more relaxed when facing the Feds.  

: S >it would be hard, given the circumstances of the particular
: S >case, and the many others (see the above list) who HAVE obeyed the 
: S >rules and aren't being prosecuted, for a civil liberties organization
: S >(IMHO) to see its way clear to ponying up the money for a defense.

: Many people have been anxious to test the status of crypto as a munition 
: and the First Amendment protection of source code and software for a 
: long time.  There will be no problems obtaining money to mount a strong 
: defense.

: S >This may end up not a test of constitutional principles, but of the 
: S >government's right to make reasonable rules. I would be surprised if
: S >such a case can be won against that right. But what do I know--I'm not 
: S >an attorney.

: The Feds case against Phil will be rough because he took pains not to 
: actually export PGP and hasn't written code for many releases.  Also if 
: Phil is to be busted for not taking steps to prevent the export of PGP, 
: NIST should be busted for not taking steps to prevent the export of 
: the DES.  Nets and export controls don't mix well.  Criminal convictions 
: require "proof beyond a reasonable doubt and to a moral certainty" which 
: is hard to establish when the defense can demonstrate how children can 
: export software for "free" in 2 minutes without even breathing hard.

